Quartz 1.5.1 has the following code on its _org.quartz.JobExecutionContext_ constructor:

{code}
    public JobExecutionContext(Scheduler scheduler,
            TriggerFiredBundle firedBundle, Job job) {
...
        this.jobDataMap.setMutable(false);
        this.trigger.getJobDataMap().setMutable(false);
    }
{code}

The _setMutable_ method of the trigger's _JobDataMap_ implementation, _org.quartz.utils.DirtyFlagMap_, looks like this:

{code}
    public void setMutable(boolean mutable) {
        this.locked = !mutable;
        if(locked)
            map = Collections.unmodifiableMap(map);
        else
            map = new HashMap(map);
    }
{code}

If the caller passes in _mutable false_ (and the state does not get changed in the meanwhile), the internal map will be decorated with the _java.util.Collections.UnmodifiableMap_.

This code is quite dangerous, because as it seems the above mentioned caller (_JobExecutionContext_ constructor) is the only caller in the framework. If a job runs with a high-frequency for a few weeks, the reference chain could grow to a level where an iteration over the map's entries could result in an exhaustions of the thread's max stack size.

The code was introduced somewhere in between Quartz 1.4.5 (the version JIRA was on before) and 1.5.1. It was removed as part of [QUARTZ-458|http://jira.opensymphony.com/browse/QUARTZ-458] for 1.6, thus upgrading to this version should remove the threat of building up a harmful state.

The caller iterating over the trigger's _JobDataMap_ is yet to be identified. This is due to the nature of the logging of the _StackOverflowError_ not containing the root stack frame anymore. It would be enough if _setMutable(true)_ is called after a couple of weeks, thus the _HashMap_ constructor would iterate over the map in order to attach the values and would thus hit the _StackOverflowError_. Now we know that the actual call has to be in the Quartz thread executing JIRA's _ServiceRunner_, since its run method does not reference the _jobExecutionContext_ anywhere. 

My guess would be that it is _job = qs.getJobFactory().newJob(firedBundle)_ in _org.quartz.core.JobRunShell.initialize(QuartzScheduler, TriggerFiredBundle)_ which would either have to directly iterate over the trigger's _JobDataMap_ or construct sth. which would do that lazily in order to satisfy the contract as laid out in _org.quartz.JobDataMap_:

{quote}
The _JobExecutionContext_ passed to a Job at execution time also contains a convenience _JobDataMap_ that is the result of *merging the contents of the trigger's _JobDataMap_ (if any)* over the _Job_'s _JobDataMap_ (if any).
{quote}

E.g. org.quartz.simpl.PropertySettingJobFactory does the following:

{code}
    public Job newJob(TriggerFiredBundle bundle) throws SchedulerException {

        Job job = super.newJob(bundle);
        
        JobDataMap jobDataMap = new JobDataMap();
        jobDataMap.putAll(bundle.getJobDetail().getJobDataMap());
        jobDataMap.putAll(bundle.getTrigger().getJobDataMap());

        setBeanProps(job, jobDataMap);
        
        return job;
    }
{code}

If this theory is correct, every JIRA instance >= 4.3 will eventually run into this problem if not being restarted.

